1. Introduction¶

In this prediction chanllege, The target is to predict who will most likely click on the ad. This project will help understand the customer behavior and category, then Ad can be accurately deployed for different users.

For advertisement deployment, the most import metrics is precision, while recall is crucial for Virus infection detection. As such, the profit of advertising deployment are from True positive and True Negative, and penalty is from False Positive . If each customer that we target with our ad campaign and clicks on the ad, we get an overall profit of 1000 USD. However, if we target a customer that ends up not clicking on the ad, we incur a net loss of 1050 USD. If a customer that was not targeted by the campaign and who clicks on the ad, we will get an overall profit of 1100USD

Outlier detection¶

In [69]:
# We define a outlier remove function

def iqr_outlier_rm(df_input):
    # use the np.percentile as the indicator
    # lq, uq = np.percentile(df_input, [25, 75])
    quantile = df_input.quantile([.25, .75], axis=0)
    lq, uq = quantile.iloc[0], quantile.iloc[1]
    IQR = uq - lq
    lower = lq - 1.5 * IQR
    upper = uq + 1.5 * IQR
    
    # be aware that the slice numpy or pandas using bool --> df[[True, True, False]]
    # inside is a lit
    # we need to transfer the time series data into list
    # This is not slice according to index
    
    # slice according to the element --> be aware of that delete the NAN value
    return df_input[(df_input >= lower) & (df_input <= upper)].dropna()

In [96]:
# show the info of the data
sns.set_style("whitegrid", {'axes.grid' : False})

def data_info(data):
    return data.info()

def creating_boxplots(size, target, features, data):
    plt.figure(figsize=size)
    for i in range(len(features)):
        plt.subplot(5, 3, i+1)
        sns.boxplot(x=target, y=features[i], data=data)
        plt.grid(False)

def creating_distplot(size, data, features):
    plt.figure(figsize=size)
    for i in range(len(features)):
        plt.subplot(5, 3, i+1)
        sns.distplot(data[features[i]])

def crossCorrelation(data):
    corr = data.corr()
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    sns.heatmap(corr,
                cmap='Blues',
                xticklabels=corr.columns.values,
                yticklabels=corr.columns.values)

For the skewed data, we use the log transformation¶

3.3 Feature Engineering¶

3.3.1 Skewed Features: Log Transform¶

Before performing machine learning, we will transform some features to avoid introducing some bias due to the overall distribution of the latter. As mentioned previously, we have some skewed distributions and they can make our models underperformed. To potentially solve this issue, we will apply a logarithmic transformation to reduce the effect of outliers and reduce the distribution's range.

  • The data of age feature is right skewed, there has three method to solve the skewed data:
    • Logarithmic transformation --> after transformation -0.07
    • Square root transformation --> after transformation 0.24
    • Box-Cox transformation --> after transformation -0.0006 --> reduce the data size

def tune_model(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, model_proposed):
    from warnings import simplefilter
    # ignore all future warnings
    simplefilter(action='ignore', category=FutureWarning)
    
    roc_figure = []
    training_model = []
    
    for model, parameters in model_proposed.items():
        print ( "\n")
        print( "====================={}==============================".format(model))
        if model == "LogisticRegression":
            estimator = LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs', max_iter=200, random_state=42, penalty='l2')

        elif model == "SVC":
            estimator = SVC(probability=True)

        elif model == "RandomForestClassifier":
            estimator = RandomForestClassifier()
        
        elif model == "KNN":
            estimator = KNeighborsClassifier()
            
        
        scorer = make_scorer(fbeta_score, beta=0.5)
        grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, 
                                param_grid=parameters, 
                                scoring=scorer)
        grid_fit = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)
        best_clf = grid_fit.best_estimator_
        best_predictions = best_clf.predict(X_train)
        
        best_predictions_prob = best_clf.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1]
        
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, best_predictions_prob)
        roc_figure.append((model,fpr, tpr, thresholds))
        
        training_model.append(best_clf)
        # report the scores
        print("\nOptimized Model {}\n-----".format(model))
        print("Finaly accuracy score on the testing data: {:.4f}".format(accuracy_score(y_train, best_predictions)))
        print("Final F-score on the testing data: {:.4f}".format(fbeta_score(y_train, best_predictions, beta=0.5)))
        print("\nOptimized Model {}\n-----".format(model))
        
        print(best_clf)
    
    
    return training_model, best_predictions, roc_figure

def summary_metrics(y, y_pred):
    confmat = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)
    TP = confmat[0,0]
    FN = confmat[0,1]
    FP = confmat[1,0]
    TN = confmat[1,1]
    
    # print the confusion matrix
    print("Confusion matrix:\n", confmat)
    
    # print the accuracy score
    print("Accuracy:", round(accuracy_score(y, y_pred), 2))
    
    # recall
    print("Sensitivity:", round(recall_score(y, y_pred),2))
    
    # print the Sensitivity/recall / true positive rate
    print("Precision:", round(precision_score(y, y_pred), 2))
    
    print("")
    print("DETAILS")
    
    # RETURN ON TP
    print("True Positive:", round((float(TP) * 1000), 2))
    
    # RETURN ON FP
    print("False Positive:", round(float(FP) * -1050, 2))
    
    # RETURN ON FN
    print("False Negative:", round((float(FN) * 1100), 2))
    
    # RETURN ON TN
    print("True Negative:", round((float(TN) * 0), 2))
    
    
    # Return on investment
    investment_return = (TP * 1000) + (FP * -1050) + (FN * 1100) * (TN * 0)
    
    print("Profit:", round(float(investment_return), 2), "$")

6. Applicable Recommendation¶

  • According to our model, we can identify potential clients by getting information about users on:

    • Daily Time Spent on site
    • Daily Internet Usage
    • Age
    • Area income

    By getting this information, we can target new customers with our ad campaign to maximize the chance of a return on investment. We can speculate that the level of education could correlate with our finding since it was been previously reported that there is a correlation between the income and the level of education. From our exploratory data analysis and our machine learning results, our targeted population would be customers with:

    • Lower income
    • Spending less time on the website
    • Spending less time on the internet
    • Who are older than our average sample (mean around 40 years old)

Also by increasing our threshold from our model, we can minimize the false positives (e.g., minimizing loss) which optimizes our business approach.
